    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "There's some good ideas here, but i'm not convinced about the specific abstraction that you're proposing in #8786.\n\nI believe a cleaner appropach would be to start by splitting `Requires` into two interfaces that handle its two (actually quite seperable) jobs:\n-  `Requires<>` (keeping the same name) - used when this trait can't operate / doesn't make sense without the named trait.  Used primarily by lint tests to check for bogus rule setups and docs generation.  Does not affect the trait load order.\n-  `InitializeAfter<>` - used when this trait accesses another trait (if it is available) from the constructor.  Affects the load order, and can be used together with `Requires<>` if a trait is needed from a constructor, or by itself if the dependency is optional.  There are a bunch of cases where we currently use Lazy to work around the lack of this capability which could be cleaned up.\n\nOnce this is in place, we can then add (in a second PR) `RequiresSingleton<>` and `Uses<>` and cover all of your use cases with a smaller number of clearly named tags.\n\nWould you be willing to do these changes as a prerequisite PR first?\n"
  },
